[TEXT]
STATEMENT: >>>
This document specifies the functional requirements for Mouse Protocol Detection
(feature id MOUSE, Tier 4 Stretch Goal). The feature detects, at process startup,
which mouse encoding protocols and tracking modes the controlling terminal supports,
using DECRPM queries (CSI ? Ps $ p) for modes 1000 (X10 button tracking), 1002
(button-event tracking), 1003 (any-event tracking), 1006 (SGR mouse encoding), 1015
(URXVT encoding), and 1016 (SGR pixel-precision encoding). On the Linux text console
(TERM=linux), DECRPM responses are unreliable and mouse input is provided by the GPM
daemon; this path is detected via a lightweight heuristic. On Win32 Console (non-PTY),
mouse input is available through the Console API, not DECRPM.

Detection reuses the OSC Query Infrastructure (OSC-INFRA, REQ-OSC) sentinel pattern and
the DECRPM query infrastructure (REQ-RPM): multiple DECRPM queries may be batched in a
single sentinel-bounded session, followed by one DA1 sentinel (CSI c) as the response
boundary. The result is a structured record capturing per-mode booleans and a preferred
encoding, cached for the process lifetime.

SPARK Silver is the target for pure logic (DECRPM response parsing, cascade resolution).
All I/O, termios management, and OS dispatch are classified Ada FFI (SPARK_Mode => Off),
consistent with OSC-INFRA, CYGWIN, and KITTY-KB patterns.
<<<

[SECTION]
TITLE: Result Types

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-001
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Mouse_Encoding Enumeration Type
STATEMENT: >>>
The library shall provide an enumeration type Mouse_Encoding whose values represent the
encoding schemes that may be available for mouse event reporting:

  Unknown       -- Detection has not been performed or could not be completed (stdin not
                   a TTY, foreground guard failed, probe timed out entirely, Win32
                   DECRPM path not applicable).
  None          -- Detection was performed successfully but no supported mouse encoding
                   was found (all queried modes returned Not_Recognized).
  X10           -- Classic X10 encoding only: ESC [ M Cb Cx Cy (three raw bytes, range
                   limited to columns/rows 1-222). Indicates mode 1000 was recognised
                   but modes 1006 and 1016 were not.
  URXVT         -- URXVT decimal encoding: ESC [ Cb ; Cx ; Cy M (decimal, unlimited
                   range). Indicates mode 1015 was recognised but modes 1006 and 1016
                   were not.
  SGR           -- SGR encoding: ESC [ < Cb ; Cx ; Cy M/m (decimal, unlimited range,
                   distinguishes press from release). Indicates mode 1006 was recognised
                   but mode 1016 was not.
  SGR_Pixels    -- SGR pixel-precision encoding: same format as SGR but Cx, Cy are pixel
                   coordinates. Indicates mode 1016 was recognised.

The enumeration shall be defined in a package Termicap.Mouse (or a child thereof) with
SPARK_Mode => On.

Mouse_Encoding represents the BEST available encoding (the result of the preference
cascade, FUNC-MSE-008). It is distinct from the per-mode Boolean flags in
Mouse_Capabilities (FUNC-MSE-002), which record the full set of recognised modes.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The five non-Unknown/None values correspond to the four encoding families documented in the
global synthesis (§2.6): X10, SGR, SGR-pixels, and URXVT. URXVT (mode 1015) is included
because several reference implementations (tcell, notcurses) probe it and it is still found
in urxvt-derived terminals. The Unknown/None distinction mirrors the Keyboard_Protocol design
in FUNC-KKB-001: Unknown = probing failed; None = probing succeeded but found nothing. Callers
that need a conservative default when probing fails should treat Unknown the same as None.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-002
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Mouse_Capabilities Result Record
STATEMENT: >>>
The library shall provide a record type Mouse_Capabilities that aggregates the complete
mouse protocol detection result. The record shall contain:

  -- Encoding preference (derived, FUNC-MSE-008):
  Best_Encoding         : Mouse_Encoding
    -- The highest-preference encoding available, per the cascade in FUNC-MSE-008.
    -- Mouse_Encoding'First (Unknown) when detection was not performed.

  -- Per-mode support flags (FUNC-MSE-006):
  Supports_X10          : Boolean
    -- True when DECRPM mode 1000 (X11 button tracking) was recognised (status /= 0).
  Supports_Button_Event : Boolean
    -- True when DECRPM mode 1002 (button-event / drag tracking) was recognised.
  Supports_Any_Event    : Boolean
    -- True when DECRPM mode 1003 (any motion tracking) was recognised.
  Supports_URXVT        : Boolean
    -- True when DECRPM mode 1015 (URXVT decimal encoding) was recognised.
  Supports_SGR          : Boolean
    -- True when DECRPM mode 1006 (SGR decimal encoding) was recognised.
  Supports_SGR_Pixels   : Boolean
    -- True when DECRPM mode 1016 (SGR pixel-precision encoding) was recognised.

  -- Platform-specific flags (FUNC-MSE-010, FUNC-MSE-011):
  Win32_Console_Mouse   : Boolean
    -- True when the Win32 platform gate fired and Console API mouse is available.
    -- Mutually exclusive with a probed result: when True, all Supports_* fields
    -- are False and Best_Encoding is Unknown.
  GPM_Available         : Boolean
    -- True when the Linux/GPM path was detected (TERM=linux and /dev/gpmctl exists).
    -- When True, Supports_* fields are False (DECRPM not used on this path) and
    -- Best_Encoding is Unknown (GPM provides its own event stream, not a DECRPM encoding).

  -- Probe metadata:
  Probed                : Boolean
    -- True when an active DECRPM probe sequence was attempted (stdin was a TTY,
    -- foreground guard passed, probe sequence was sent). False when the result was
    -- determined without probing (Win32 gate, GPM heuristic, non-TTY, foreground guard).

The type shall be declared with SPARK_Mode => On.

The canonical "no result" value shall be:
  Best_Encoding = Unknown, all Supports_* = False,
  Win32_Console_Mouse = False, GPM_Available = False, Probed = False.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Orthogonal Boolean flags per mode (rather than a set or bitmask) are preferred for SPARK
provability: each field can be individually reasoned about and individually tested. Best_Encoding
is a derived summary (computed by the cascade in FUNC-MSE-008) so that callers that only need
"what encoding should I use?" get a single enum value without needing to implement their own
cascade logic. The Win32_Console_Mouse and GPM_Available flags are additive: they do not
conflict with each other in theory, but in practice exactly one of {DECRPM-probed, Win32,
GPM} paths fires. Declaring them as independent Booleans preserves a clean SPARK type while
being honest about the platform semantics. The Probed field mirrors the pattern from
Keyboard_Capability (FUNC-KKB-003) to enable test-harness introspection.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Detection Algorithm — DECRPM Queries

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-003
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: DECRPM Mode Constants for Mouse Protocols
STATEMENT: >>>
The library shall define the following named constants for the DEC private mode numbers
used in mouse protocol detection. These shall be defined as values of the Mode_Id subtype
(FUNC-RPM-001), in the Termicap.Mouse package or a dedicated child package:

  MODE_MOUSE_X10            : constant Mode_Id := 1000;
    -- X11/X10 mouse button tracking (press and release events only).
  MODE_MOUSE_BUTTON_EVENT   : constant Mode_Id := 1002;
    -- Button-event tracking: includes button-press, button-release, and drag motion.
  MODE_MOUSE_ANY_EVENT      : constant Mode_Id := 1003;
    -- Any-motion tracking: includes all motion events regardless of button state.
  MODE_MOUSE_URXVT          : constant Mode_Id := 1015;
    -- URXVT decimal encoding extension for unlimited coordinate range.
  MODE_MOUSE_SGR            : constant Mode_Id := 1006;
    -- SGR decimal encoding with press/release distinction via M/m terminator.
  MODE_MOUSE_SGR_PIXELS     : constant Mode_Id := 1016;
    -- SGR pixel-precision encoding: coordinates in pixels, not character cells.

All constants shall use ALL_CAPS_WITH_UNDERSCORES naming per the Ada coding standard.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Collecting the mode constants in one place (following the pattern of MODE_MOUSE_X11 and
MODE_MOUSE_SGR already present in FUNC-RPM-001) ensures consistency between the DECRPM
infrastructure and the mouse feature. The six modes above are the complete set queried by
tcell and notcurses per the global synthesis (§2.6). Mode 1015 (URXVT) is included despite
being less common: it is still present in urxvt-derived terminals and foot, and the cost of
one additional DECRPM query is negligible when queries are batched (FUNC-MSE-005).
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-004
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: DECRPM Query Sequence for Mouse Modes
STATEMENT: >>>
The library shall probe mouse mode availability by issuing DECRPM queries (CSI ? Ps $ p)
for the following modes, in the stated order:

  1. MODE_MOUSE_X10          (1000)
  2. MODE_MOUSE_BUTTON_EVENT (1002)
  3. MODE_MOUSE_ANY_EVENT    (1003)
  4. MODE_MOUSE_URXVT        (1015)
  5. MODE_MOUSE_SGR          (1006)
  6. MODE_MOUSE_SGR_PIXELS   (1016)

Each query shall be issued via the DECRPM infrastructure (FUNC-RPM-005 or equivalent
Termicap.DECRPM.Query function). The queries shall be issued as part of a
sentinel-bounded probe session (FUNC-OSC-006): all six query bytes are written to the
terminal file descriptor, followed immediately by a single DA1 sentinel (CSI c). The
session is bounded by the arrival of the DA1 response (CSI ? 1 ; <Psc> c or the first
DA1-shaped response), providing a firm deadline for the entire batch.

Each DECRPM response shall match the pattern:
  CSI ? <Ps> ; <Pm> $ y
where Ps is the mode number and Pm is the status code (0–4, per FUNC-RPM-002).
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Batching all six queries in a single sentinel-bounded session (one DA1 sentinel for the
entire batch) is more efficient than six independent sessions (each with its own DA1 and
termios save/restore cycle). This is safe because the DECRPM responses for the six modes
are all independently parseable by mode number (Ps) in the CSI ? Ps ; Pm $ y response,
so interleaved responses can still be attributed to the correct mode. The query order
(tracking modes first, then encoding modes) follows notcurses and tcell practice. If a
terminal returns responses out of order, the parser shall match by Ps, not by position.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-005
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Batched Query Session — Single Sentinel for All Six Queries
STATEMENT: >>>
The six DECRPM mouse queries shall be dispatched in a single batched terminal session,
reusing the OSC-INFRA session lifecycle (FUNC-OSC-001 through FUNC-OSC-006):

  1. Open /dev/tty via FUNC-OSC-001 (Open_TTY).
  2. Save terminal attributes via FUNC-OSC-002 (Save_Termios).
  3. Enter raw mode via FUNC-OSC-003 (Set_Raw_Mode).
  4. Write all six DECRPM query sequences to the terminal file descriptor via
     FUNC-OSC-005 (Write_Query), followed by the DA1 sentinel bytes.
  5. Read responses until the DA1 sentinel pattern is recognised, accumulating
     all bytes received before the sentinel via FUNC-OSC-006 (Sentinel_Query).
  6. Restore terminal attributes unconditionally via FUNC-OSC-002 (Restore_Termios).
  7. Close /dev/tty via FUNC-OSC-001 (Close_TTY).

The mouse detection function shall not call tcgetattr, tcsetattr, select(), read(), or
write() directly; all such calls shall be mediated through the OSC-INFRA interface,
consistent with FUNC-KKB-012.

On POSIX platforms, the detection shall use the configured OSC-INFRA timeout
(FUNC-MSE-012) for the entire batched session.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
A single batched session avoids the overhead of six raw-mode enter/restore cycles, which
would be particularly noticeable over SSH. The terminal is left in raw mode for the
minimal duration needed to collect all responses; this is the standard pattern for
multi-query probes in notcurses and tcell. Unconditional termios restore (step 6) mirrors
FUNC-KKB-015 and is the single most important safety invariant of any raw-mode probe.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-006
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: DECRPM Response Status Interpretation for Mouse Modes
STATEMENT: >>>
For each DECRPM response received before the DA1 sentinel, the library shall extract
the mode number Ps and status code Pm per the Mode_Status mapping in FUNC-RPM-002.
The library shall set the corresponding Supports_* flag in Mouse_Capabilities as follows:

  Mode_Status = Not_Recognized (Pm = 0): Supports_* := False
    -- The terminal does not implement this mode at all.
  Mode_Status = Set             (Pm = 1): Supports_* := True
    -- Mode is currently enabled; terminal recognises it.
  Mode_Status = Reset           (Pm = 2): Supports_* := True
    -- Mode is currently disabled but the terminal recognises it and can enable it.
  Mode_Status = Permanently_Set (Pm = 3): Supports_* := True
    -- Mode is always on; terminal fully supports it.
  Mode_Status = Permanently_Reset (Pm = 4): Supports_* := True
    -- Mode is always off but the terminal recognises the mode number.

Status codes 1, 2, 3, and 4 all result in Supports_* = True because they indicate the
terminal implements the mode. Only status 0 (Not_Recognized) yields Supports_* = False.

If no response is received for a given mode before the DA1 sentinel arrives (the terminal
did not emit a response for that Ps), Supports_* shall remain False.

The response parser shall be a pure SPARK function (FUNC-MSE-007).
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
This interpretation follows the DECRPM semantics documented in FUNC-RPM-002: the key
distinction is whether the terminal RECOGNISES the mode number, not whether the mode is
currently enabled. A terminal may have SGR mouse encoding reset (status 2) but still
support it — the application is responsible for activating it with DECSET. Treating all
non-zero statuses as "supported" is consistent with tcell's DECRPM usage and with the
purpose of this query: capability detection, not current state inspection.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-007
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: DECRPM Mouse Response Parser (SPARK Silver)
STATEMENT: >>>
The library shall provide a pure SPARK function that parses a single DECRPM response byte
buffer and extracts the mode number and status. Its representative specification is:

  type DECRPM_Parse_Result is record
     Valid  : Boolean;
     Mode   : Mode_Id;
     Status : Mode_Status;
  end record
     with SPARK_Mode => On;

  function Parse_Mouse_DECRPM_Response
     (Buffer : Byte_Array;
      Length : Natural)
      return DECRPM_Parse_Result
     with SPARK_Mode => On,
          Global     => null,
          Pre        => Length <= Buffer'Length,
          Post       => True;

The function shall return Valid = True when Buffer (1 .. Length) matches:

  ESC (0x1B) '[' (0x5B) '?' (0x3F) <mode_digits>+ ';' (0x3B) <status_digit> '$' (0x24) 'y' (0x79)

where <mode_digits>+ is one or more ASCII decimal digits encoding the mode number Ps, and
<status_digit> is a single ASCII decimal digit in the range '0'..'4' encoding Pm.

The function shall decode Ps into Mode and Pm into Status using the Mode_Status mapping
(FUNC-RPM-002). It shall return Valid = False for any buffer that does not match this
pattern, including partial responses, missing ';', missing '$', or Pm outside 0–4.

Bits beyond the valid pattern shall not cause a range error; the function shall not raise
for any buffer content.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
A dedicated pure SPARK parser for the DECRPM mouse response follows the same structural
pattern as Parse_Kitty_Response (FUNC-KKB-006) and Parse_XTerm_Keyboard_Response
(FUNC-KKB-008): pure parsing logic in a SPARK Silver function, independently testable
with synthetic byte arrays. The pre-condition Length <= Buffer'Length is the minimal
safety contract, preventing reads beyond the valid portion of a stack-allocated buffer.
Returning a record (Valid + Mode + Status) rather than a Boolean keeps the caller logic
simple: a single call extracts everything needed to update the corresponding Supports_*
flag in Mouse_Capabilities.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Encoding Cascade and Preference Resolution

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-008
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Best_Encoding Cascade — SGR_Pixels > SGR > URXVT > X10 > None
STATEMENT: >>>
After all DECRPM responses have been parsed and the Supports_* flags set, the library
shall derive Best_Encoding via the following preference cascade, evaluated in order:

  Step 1: if Supports_SGR_Pixels  => Best_Encoding := SGR_Pixels
  Step 2: else if Supports_SGR    => Best_Encoding := SGR
  Step 3: else if Supports_URXVT  => Best_Encoding := URXVT
  Step 4: else if Supports_X10    => Best_Encoding := X10
  Step 5: else                     => Best_Encoding := None

The cascade is evaluated only after a successful DECRPM probe session (Probed = True).
When probing was not performed or failed entirely (Probed = False), Best_Encoding shall
remain Unknown.

The cascade shall be implemented as a pure SPARK function:

  function Resolve_Best_Encoding
     (Caps : Mouse_Capabilities)
      return Mouse_Encoding
     with SPARK_Mode => On,
          Global     => null,
          Pre        => True,
          Post       => True;
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The preference order SGR_Pixels > SGR > URXVT > X10 > None reflects the capability
hierarchy: SGR pixel encoding (1016) provides the richest information (pixel coordinates),
SGR (1006) provides unlimited coordinate range with press/release distinction, URXVT (1015)
provides unlimited range without press/release, and X10 (1000) is the legacy baseline.
URXVT is placed above X10 (not below SGR) because it at least provides unlimited
coordinates; X10's byte-limited range is strictly inferior. The cascade deliberately ignores
tracking mode flags (Supports_Button_Event, Supports_Any_Event) in the encoding decision:
the encoding scheme is orthogonal to the tracking mode (whether drag or motion events are
reported). Applications that need drag events can check Supports_Button_Event independently.
The pure SPARK function Resolve_Best_Encoding makes the cascade independently testable and
provable without any I/O.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Platform Gating

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-009
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Pre-Conditions and TTY / Foreground Guards
STATEMENT: >>>
The mouse protocol detection function shall apply the following guards before initiating
any DECRPM probe, in order:

  Guard 1 — Win32 Platform Gate (FUNC-MSE-010):
    Evaluated first on Windows. If stdin is a Win32 Console handle (GetConsoleMode
    succeeds), return with Win32_Console_Mouse set per FUNC-MSE-010, without probing.

  Guard 2 — Linux/GPM Heuristic (FUNC-MSE-011):
    Evaluated on POSIX before opening /dev/tty. If TERM=linux and /dev/gpmctl is
    accessible, return with GPM_Available = True, Probed = False, without probing.

  Guard 3 — Not a TTY:
    If Termicap.TTY.Is_TTY (Stdin) returns False, return Mouse_Capabilities with
    Best_Encoding = Unknown, Probed = False.

  Guard 4 — Not the foreground process:
    If Is_Foreground_Process (FUNC-OSC-007) returns False, return Mouse_Capabilities
    with Best_Encoding = Unknown, Probed = False.

  Guard 5 — /dev/tty not openable:
    If Open_TTY (FUNC-OSC-001) fails, return Mouse_Capabilities with
    Best_Encoding = Unknown, Probed = False.

Guards 1–5 are evaluated before entering raw mode. If all guards pass, the batched DECRPM
probe session (FUNC-MSE-005) is executed.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The guard ordering mirrors FUNC-KKB-009 and FUNC-KKB-011. Win32 and GPM gates are placed
before the generic TTY/foreground checks because they are platform-specific short-circuits
that do not require opening /dev/tty. The GPM guard (guard 2) precedes the TTY check to
avoid the overhead of opening /dev/tty on a Linux text console where DECRPM would fail
anyway. Guards 3 and 4 follow the OSC-INFRA pattern established in FUNC-OSC-007 and
FUNC-OSC-008, protecting against probing in non-interactive or background processes.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-010
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Win32 Platform Gate — Console API Mouse
STATEMENT: >>>
On the Windows platform, before initiating any DECRPM probe, the mouse detection function
shall check whether stdin is a Win32 Console handle by calling Win32.Wincon.GetConsoleMode
on the standard input handle (STD_INPUT_HANDLE).

If GetConsoleMode returns Win32.TRUE (genuine Windows Console, not a Cygwin/MSYS2 PTY),
the function shall return Mouse_Capabilities with:
  Win32_Console_Mouse := True
  Best_Encoding       := Unknown
  all Supports_*      := False
  Probed              := False

and shall not issue any DECRPM queries.

If GetConsoleMode returns Win32.FALSE (Cygwin/MSYS2 PTY or other pipe), the Win32 gate
does not fire and detection proceeds to guard 2 (FUNC-MSE-009), following the POSIX path.

On POSIX platforms (Linux, macOS, BSD), the Win32 gate is skipped entirely; guard 2 is
the first check evaluated.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Win32_Console_Mouse = True signals to the caller that mouse input is available via the
Windows Console API (ReadConsoleInput with MOUSE_EVENT records), not via DECRPM. The
caller is responsible for using the appropriate API; this library detects availability only.
The GetConsoleMode predicate reuses the same Windows Console detection already present in
FUNC-WIN-003 and FUNC-KKB-010, keeping the Windows gate consistent across features.
Cygwin/MSYS2 PTYs pass POSIX probing (they support DECRPM escape sequences through the
PTY layer), so they correctly fall through to the POSIX detection path.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-011
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Linux Console / GPM Fallback Detection
STATEMENT: >>>
On POSIX platforms, before opening /dev/tty, the mouse detection function shall check
whether the current environment indicates a Linux text console with GPM support, using
the following heuristic:

  Condition: TERM environment variable equals "linux"
         AND the socket file /dev/gpmctl is accessible (Ada.Directories.Exists or
             equivalent check returns True)

If this condition holds, the function shall return Mouse_Capabilities with:
  GPM_Available  := True
  Best_Encoding  := Unknown
  all Supports_* := False
  Probed         := False

and shall not issue any DECRPM queries.

If TERM=linux but /dev/gpmctl does not exist, GPM is not running; the function shall
proceed to guard 3 (FUNC-MSE-009), issue the DECRPM probe, and expect all modes to
return Not_Recognized (Best_Encoding = None).

On non-Linux platforms or when TERM /= "linux", this heuristic is skipped.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The Linux text console (virtual terminal, TERM=linux) does not implement DEC private mode
queries; sending DECRPM to a Linux console produces no response, causing the detection to
time out and return Best_Encoding = None. Mouse support on the Linux console is provided
exclusively by the GPM (General Purpose Mouse) daemon via the /dev/gpmctl Unix domain
socket. Detecting GPM via the existence of /dev/gpmctl (rather than attempting to connect
to it) is intentionally lightweight: we are detecting capability, not establishing a session.
A more thorough approach (connect, send a GPM_OPEN request) would be more accurate but adds
significant complexity and a latency risk for a detection-only library. Using Ada.Directories.Exists
avoids any SPARK_Mode issues and is already used in the Cygwin detection path. The TERM=linux
condition (rather than checking /proc/tty/drivers or similar) is the same heuristic used by
tcell and notcurses: it is well-established and has negligible false-positive rate on modern
systems. An alternative design considered was to probe DECRPM anyway and treat a timeout as
a GPM hint; this was rejected because it adds a 1-second timeout delay on every Linux
console session.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Multiplexer Awareness

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-012
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Should
TITLE: Terminal Multiplexer Caveat for DECRPM Responses
STATEMENT: >>>
The mouse protocol detection function shall be aware that terminal multiplexers (tmux,
GNU screen) may intercept, swallow, or rewrite DECRPM responses:

  - Under tmux: DECRPM responses for mouse modes may be returned with values that reflect
    tmux's own state rather than the outer terminal's capabilities.
  - Under GNU screen: DECRPM queries may receive no response, causing a total timeout.

For v1, the library shall adopt strategy (a): attempt the DECRPM probe regardless of
multiplexer presence, accept whatever responses are received, and document the limitation.
The library shall detect multiplexer presence via the TMUX and STY environment variables
(already available from the TERM-ID feature): if TMUX is set (tmux) or STY is set (screen),
the returned Mouse_Capabilities record shall have an additional diagnostic note, but the
Supports_* fields shall be populated with whatever DECRPM responded.

DCS passthrough wrapping (strategy b) for transparent outer-terminal probing is deferred
to a future version and shall be noted as a known limitation in the implementation.

The multiplexer detection relies on existing TERM-ID infrastructure; this requirement
does not introduce new OS calls.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Strategy (a) — probe anyway, accept partial results — is the approach used by tcell and
crossterm for multiplexer environments. It is pragmatic: the DECRPM responses under tmux
reflect tmux's supported mouse modes, which is often sufficient for callers (applications
running inside tmux still interact with the tmux mouse model). DCS passthrough (strategy b,
used by some notcurses builds for SGR pixel detection) is more correct but requires
reconstructing the outer-terminal response through the multiplexer's DCS passthrough
mechanism, which is complex to implement and test. Deferring it avoids blocking this
feature on multiplexer DCS support. The diagnostic note (that a multiplexer was detected)
gives callers the option to handle this case specially without the library making the
decision for them.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Timeout Behaviour

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-013
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Probe Session Timeout and Partial Response Handling
STATEMENT: >>>
The batched DECRPM mouse probe session shall use a timeout of 1000 milliseconds (1 second)
for the entire session (from writing the first query to receiving the DA1 sentinel), applied
via the OSC-INFRA timeout mechanism (FUNC-OSC-004).

On total timeout (DA1 sentinel not received within the deadline and no DECRPM responses
parsed): the function shall return Mouse_Capabilities with Best_Encoding = Unknown,
all Supports_* = False, Probed = False.

On partial response (some DECRPM responses received before DA1 arrives, even if the full
set was not returned): the function shall set Supports_* = True for modes whose responses
were received, run the cascade (FUNC-MSE-008), and return the partially-populated
Mouse_Capabilities with Probed = True.

Implementations may use a shorter timeout (minimum 100 milliseconds) on platforms where
round-trip latency to the terminal is known to be negligible (e.g., local PTY).
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The 1000 ms default matches FUNC-KKB-013 and FUNC-OSC-004. A single timeout for the
entire six-query batch (rather than per-query timeouts) is simpler and imposes no
additional overhead: the DA1 sentinel bounds the entire batch, so the timeout is defined
as the interval from batch-write to DA1-receipt. Partial response handling (returning
what was parsed rather than discarding all results on a partial timeout) is a deliberate
choice: if a slow terminal has replied for five of six modes before the deadline, those
five results are valid and useful. Best_Encoding = Unknown is reserved for total timeout
(no DA1, no usable data), distinguishing it from Best_Encoding = None (DA1 received, all
modes returned Not_Recognized).
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Error Handling

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-014
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: No-Exception Guarantee for Detect_Mouse_Protocols
STATEMENT: >>>
The top-level mouse protocol detection function Detect_Mouse_Protocols shall never
propagate an exception to its caller under any circumstances, including:

  - /dev/tty cannot be opened (FUNC-OSC-001 returns an error).
  - tcgetattr fails (FUNC-OSC-002 returns an error).
  - tcsetattr fails during raw-mode entry (FUNC-OSC-003 returns an error).
  - Write_Query returns Success = False for any DECRPM query or the DA1 sentinel.
  - The session times out entirely (FUNC-MSE-013, total timeout).
  - Any DECRPM response buffer is garbled (Parse_Mouse_DECRPM_Response returns Valid = False).
  - An EINTR or EAGAIN condition is encountered during select() or read().
  - Restore_Termios fails (its failure is silently ignored per FUNC-OSC-002).
  - Ada.Directories.Exists raises when checking /dev/gpmctl (treated as file absent).
  - GetConsoleMode raises on Windows (treated as gate-not-fired).

All failure modes shall cause the function to return either Best_Encoding = Unknown
(probe could not complete) or a partial Mouse_Capabilities (probe partially completed),
as specified in FUNC-MSE-009 and FUNC-MSE-013. The function shall not log or signal
errors to the caller; graceful degradation is the sole response.

The no-exception contract applies even when called with a null or invalid file descriptor.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The no-exception policy is universal across all Termicap detection functions, stated most
explicitly in FUNC-KKB-014 and FUNC-CYG-016. A capability-detection library that crashes
the caller on a terminal I/O error is categorically defective. The enumerate of specific
failure modes provides implementors with a comprehensive checklist.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-015
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Termios Restore on All Exit Paths
STATEMENT: >>>
The mouse protocol detection implementation shall restore terminal attributes (via
FUNC-OSC-002 Restore_Termios) on every exit path from the raw-mode section, including:

  - Normal exit after all DECRPM responses or DA1 sentinel received.
  - Exit due to partial response + DA1 received early.
  - Exit due to total timeout (no DA1 within deadline).
  - Exit due to a write failure (Write_Query returns Success = False).
  - Exit due to any other I/O error during the probe session.

Terminal attributes shall be restored before the /dev/tty file descriptor is closed,
preserving the ordering: open → save → set-raw → [probe] → restore → close. Under no
circumstances shall the function exit the raw-mode section without first attempting
Restore_Termios, even if Restore_Termios itself fails.

This requirement mirrors FUNC-KKB-015 and applies identically to the mouse probe session.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Unconditional termios restore is the single most critical safety invariant of any
raw-mode probe. Leaving the terminal in raw mode after detection would break the user's
shell session. The ordering constraint (restore before close) is identical to FUNC-KKB-015
and FUNC-OSC-002 and must not be violated even in error paths.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Caching

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-016
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: One-Probe-Per-Process Caching
STATEMENT: >>>
The library shall cache the Mouse_Capabilities result after the first call to
Detect_Mouse_Protocols and return the cached value on all subsequent calls without
re-probing. The cache shall be stored as package-level state in a protected object or
equivalent thread-safe structure, consistent with FUNC-KKB-017 and FUNC-CAP-003.

The cache shall be initialised lazily: no probe is performed until the first call to
Detect_Mouse_Protocols (or an equivalent public entry point). Eager probing at library
elaboration time is not permitted.

A caller that needs a fresh result (e.g., after a terminal change or for testing) should
be able to obtain one via a separate Detect function that bypasses the cache (analogous
to FUNC-CAP-004). This bypass is classified as a Should requirement.

The cache shall not be invalidated by SIGWINCH: mouse protocol support is invariant
across terminal resize events.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
One-probe-per-process caching is the universal pattern for all Termicap capability
detections (FUNC-CAP-003). Mouse protocol support is a property of the terminal emulator,
not of the terminal size, so it does not change during a process's lifetime. Lazy
initialisation avoids OS calls during library elaboration (unsafe). The SIGWINCH exclusion
mirrors FUNC-KKB-017 for the same reason.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: SPARK Boundary and Package Structure

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-017
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Must
TITLE: Package Structure and SPARK Boundary
STATEMENT: >>>
The mouse protocol detection feature shall be implemented in a new package
Termicap.Mouse, structured as follows:

Package specification (src/termicap-mouse.ads):
  - SPARK_Mode => On at the package level.
  - Declares Mouse_Encoding (FUNC-MSE-001) and Mouse_Capabilities (FUNC-MSE-002)
    as public types.
  - Declares the mode constants (FUNC-MSE-003) as public named constants.
  - Declares the DECRPM_Parse_Result record and Parse_Mouse_DECRPM_Response function
    (FUNC-MSE-007) with SPARK_Mode => On and Global => null contracts.
  - Declares Resolve_Best_Encoding (FUNC-MSE-008) with SPARK_Mode => On.
  - Declares the public function Detect_Mouse_Protocols with SPARK_Mode => Off
    (it calls FFI-dependent OSC-INFRA and DECRPM operations).

Package body (src/termicap-mouse.adb):
  - SPARK_Mode => Off at the package level.
  - Contains the body of Detect_Mouse_Protocols and all OS-facing helpers.
  - Contains the bodies of Parse_Mouse_DECRPM_Response and Resolve_Best_Encoding with
    SPARK_Mode => On applied locally to each subprogram body (mixed SPARK pattern,
    consistent with FUNC-KKB-018 and FUNC-CYG-017).
  - Contains the protected cache object for one-probe-per-process caching (FUNC-MSE-016).
  - Withed packages: Termicap.OSC (or its I/O subpackage), Termicap.TTY,
    Termicap.DECRPM (for Mode_Id, Mode_Status, FUNC-RPM-001, FUNC-RPM-002).

Platform-specific I/O bodies:
  - POSIX path: src/posix/termicap-mouse-io.adb (SPARK_Mode => Off).
  - Windows path: src/windows/termicap-mouse-io.adb (SPARK_Mode => Off), which adds
    the GetConsoleMode Win32 gate (FUNC-MSE-010).

File naming shall follow the project convention: lowercase with dashes matching the
package hierarchy (termicap-mouse.ads, termicap-mouse.adb).
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
The package structure mirrors Termicap.Keyboard (FUNC-KKB-018) exactly: SPARK_Mode => On
specification with pure types and parse functions, SPARK_Mode => Off body with mixed local
SPARK_Mode => On on the pure subprogram bodies, and per-OS I/O body files. The mixed SPARK
pattern (documented in ada-lessons-learned.md) avoids circular SPARK boundary issues while
keeping the pure parsing and cascade logic provable. Withing Termicap.DECRPM for the Mode_Id
and Mode_Status types avoids redefinition and ensures that the mouse constants are
interoperable with the general DECRPM infrastructure.
<<<

[/SECTION]

[SECTION]
TITLE: Integration with Capability Record

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: FUNC-MSE-018
STATUS: Approved
PRIORITY: Could
TITLE: Mouse_Capabilities Field in Terminal_Capabilities (Deferred)
STATEMENT: >>>
The Terminal_Capabilities record (FUNC-CAP-001) should be extended with a field:

  Mouse : Termicap.Mouse.Mouse_Capabilities
    -- The detected mouse protocol capabilities, populated by Detect_Mouse_Protocols
    -- on the first call to Get or Detect (FUNC-CAP-003, FUNC-CAP-004). Defaults to
    -- the canonical Unknown/empty value when mouse detection has not been performed.

Integration into Terminal_Capabilities is OUT OF SCOPE for this feature specification
and is deferred as an explicit non-goal. The integration shall be tracked as a separate
work item when MOUSE is promoted from Draft to Approved and the Tier 4 capability record
update is scheduled.

The Detect function for Terminal_Capabilities (FUNC-CAP-004) shall invoke
Detect_Mouse_Protocols as part of the sub-detector sequence when this field is present.
<<<
COMMENT: >>>
Deferring integration into Terminal_Capabilities follows the same pattern as FUNC-KKB-019:
the core detection function Detect_Mouse_Protocols is fully usable as a standalone API,
and the capability record integration can be deferred until the feature is stabilised.
This non-goal is stated explicitly to prevent implementors from feeling obligated to
modify capability_record.sdoc as part of this feature. The Should priority (vs Must)
reflects that standalone use is sufficient for Tier 4.
<<<

[/SECTION]
